I know that the volume and the surface area of a sphere of radius $R$ are related by a derivative:  $$V(R)= rac{4}{3}\pi R^3$$ $$A(R)=4\pi R^2= rac{\partial V(R)}{\partial R}$$ I am asking if an analogous relation, in the sense that it allows to know the value of the surface from the value of the volume, exists for the indicator functions. I know the indicator function of a set $\Omega\in\mathbb{R}^n $ and $\vec{x}\in\mathbb{R}^n$ is a generic point : $$ \chi_{\Omega}(\vec{x})=  egin{cases}        \hfill 1 	ext{ if } \vec{x}\in \Omega \       \hfill 0 	ext{ if } \vec{x}
otin \Omega \   \end{cases} $$ the volume of $\Omega$ is easily computed: $$V(\Omega)=\iiint_{\mathbb{R}^n} \chi_{\Omega}(\vec{x})d\vec{x} $$ Is it possible to compute the value of the surface area $A(\Omega)$ from the knowledge of $\chi(\Omega)$? Taking the derivative of  $\chi_{\Omega}(\vec{x})$ I expect to have something related to the delta function.  From an intuitive point of view, I expect the integral:  egin{equation} \iiint_{\mathbb{R}^3} ||
abla \chi_{\Omega}(\vec{x})|| d\vec{x}  	ag{*}\label{*} \end{equation} to be related to the surface area and this makes me think about a certain relationship. I also had a look online and in the book ''Shapes and Geometries Metrics, Analysis, Differential Calculus, and Optimization'' but I have not find anithing which solves my problem directtly. I have also thougt to use the divergence theorem but that would mean to find a field $\vec{F}$ whose divergence is $\chi$ and this is the countrary of what I am looking for by analaogy (something which allows me to compute the area from the derivative (gradient) of the volume). Is my "intuition correct" and if yes could you give me a detailed answer or/and a good book/reference which attacks that problem directly? ---------------EDIT--------------- I reasoned a bit more on my question and I think I have found something. In particular, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area remembered me that ''While for piecewise smooth surfaces there is a unique natural notion of surface area, if a surface is very irregular, or rough, then it may not be possible to assign an area to it at all.'' Then assuming to deal with a voulume $\Omega \in \mathbb{R}^n$ whose boundary $\partial \Omega$ is regular enough to have a well defined surface area, I reasoned as follow: the indicartor function is used to compute approximatively the surface area by implicitly assuming it to be smooth and calculating its derivative (which are nonvanishing only on the smooth-assumed boundary). This post Smooth approximation of characteristic function of a bounded open set gave me the idea: By seeing the indicator function $\chi_{\Omega}(\vec{x})$ as the limit of the following succession of functions:  egin{equation} 	f_n(\vec{x})= rac{n^3}{\pi^{ rac{3}{2}}}e^{-(n{\vec{x}})^2} \end{equation} which has integral $1$ and approaches the Dirac delta function as $n	o \infty$.  The convolution $\chi_{\Omega}*f_n$ is smooth  $ orall n$ since $f_n$ is smooth and it converges everywhere to $\chi_{\Omega}$:  egin{equation} 	[\chi_{\Omega}*f_n](\vec{x})=\int_{\mathbb R^3}\chi_{\Omega}(\vec{y})f_n(\vec{x}-\vec{y})d\vec{y} \end{equation}  egin{equation} 	
abla^k_{\vec{x}}[\chi_{\Omega}*f_n](\vec{x})=\int_{\mathbb R^3}\chi_{\Omega}(\vec{y})
abla^k_{\vec{x}}f_n(\vec{x}-\vec{y})d\vec{y} \end{equation} Therefore, using this formalism, we can define the implicit equation for the surface as:  egin{equation} 	h_n(\vec{x})=[\chi_{\Omega}*f_n](\vec{x})-0.5 \end{equation}  egin{equation}  \chi_{\Omega}(\vec{x})=	heta(h_n(\vec{x})) 	ag{**}\label{**} \end{equation} Given a 3D surface defined implicitly by $h_n(x,y,z)=0$ the normal versor to it is defined by:  egin{equation} 	\hat{N}_n= rac{
abla h_n}{||
abla h_n||} \end{equation} For finite $n$, the vector field $\hat{N}_n$ defined here is continuous and differentiable, hence we can apply the divergence theorem using $\hat{N}_n$ as a vector field:  egin{equation} 	\iiint_V( 
abla\cdot\hat{N_n}) \;	ext{d}	au=\iint_{\partial V} (\hat{N_n}\cdot\hat{N_n})\;	ext{dS}=\iint_{\partial V} 	ext{dS}= A 	ag{***}\label{***} \end{equation} Therefore we are able to compute the surface area integrating over the volume the divergence of the vector field defined by the normal to the surface. The vector field $\hat{N}_n$ defined here is continuous and differentiable in the region around the border of V for finite $n$, but as $n	o\infty$ it becomes ill defined Therefore, up to now I think that my method allows to have an approximate estimation of the area of the surface for $n$ finite, but in the limir $n	o\infty$ we have that the vector field $\hat{N}_n$ becomes ill defined and so I cannot say anything about the convergence of the area to the real value... I am now trying to show that ef{***} becomes ef{*} in the limit $n	o\infty$...intuitively this seems possible... Recalling ef{*}, we have that, using ef{**}:  egin{equation} 
abla \chi_{\Omega}(\vec{x})=\delta(h_n(\vec{x}))
abla h_n(\vec{x}) \end{equation} Hence ef{*} becomes:  egin{equation} \iiint_{\mathbb{R}^3} \delta(h_n(\vec{x})) ||
abla h_n(\vec{x})|| d\vec{x} \end{equation} Now, using the coarea formula from geometric measure theory ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirac_delta_function ): $$\int_{\mathbf{R}^n} f(\mathbf{x}) \, \delta(g(\mathbf{x})) \, d\mathbf{x} = \int_{g^{-1}(0)} rac{f(\mathbf{x})}{|\mathbf{
abla}g|}\,d\sigma(\mathbf{x}) $$ we have:  egin{equation} \iiint_{\mathbb{R}^3} \delta(h_n(\vec{x})) ||
abla h_n(\vec{x})|| d\vec{x}=\iint_{h_n^{-1}(0)}  rac{||
abla h_n(\vec{x})||}{||
abla h_n(\vec{x})||}dS=\iint_{h_n^{-1}(0)} dS \end{equation} Therefore I have proved that ef{*} is a good definition of the surface area. Now the question is how well ef{***} approximates the area

